post_text:
Exciting News!!

We are determined to get books into the hands of our young readers. As a result, we are very excited to announce that with our next learning material pick up (Monday, April 13th), we will be able to include library books! Students have a new account in Destiny Catalog that they can use to place books on hold. Next week staff will pull those books off the shelves and into the next bag that goes home with your family.

Please refer to the email sent on April 7, 2020 for specific instructions on how to place a book on hold.

The deadline to make requests will be 8:00 am on Thursday, April 9th.

Please contact Jennah Verhey jennah.verhey@delanoschols.org, Jill York jill.york@delanoschools.org or call the
Media Center at ext. 1330 if you have any questions

post_text: We're excited to tell you about our only major fundraiser this school year, the Apex Leadership Co. Event! Apex is a local company and will be on campus for two weeks teaching our students about leadership and fitness. During the Apex program, students will be challenged to get pledges for the laps they will complete on the day of the fun run. Funds raised this year will be used to buy books for our classroom libraries. Please look for more info about the program and ways to support our school as we get closer to the event.

post_text:
WOW! Thank you to all the students who generously donated Halloween candy.

The candy is being collected by the Wright County Area Blue Star Mothers. For the past 12 years, this chapter does a holiday project of hand decorating Christmas stockings. The stockings are then filled with goodies, candy, and hand-made cards from the community. The candy donated will help fill the stockings. The stockings are sent to our military members from Minnesota who are deployed and their children.

post_text:
November is gratitude month at DES. And we are very grateful for our generous families!

First and Second grade created about 80 fleece blankets for children in foster care, crisis nursery, and families/people in need.

Some blanket will have a saying embroidered on it with a special saying such as “You are Loved,” and “You are Strong,” and “You are Amazing.”

A special thank you to DES parents Sara Kvasnicka and Jill VanBeusekom for your assistance with this project. DES first and second graders have been learning about kindness and will continue to do Acts of Kindness throughout the year!

post_text:
DES teachers Ginger Diethart and Lori Burns ended their teaching careers on Monday.
We celebrated their retirements earlier last week as they received their honorary retirement bell.
On behalf of the Delano Public School District, we thank you for dedication to your students and the families you have impacted during your career! We wish you the best in retirement!

post_text: If you missed tonight’s Delano Public Schools School Board Meeting, you missed a very informative presentation by our local Brownie Troop and DES students. The girls prepared videos and a presentation board outlining their concerns regarding crosswalk safety around DES and DIS. Superintendent Schoen and the administrative team will be reviewing the proposal and potential changes over the final weeks of the school year. Great job Nora, Ella, Vivian, Ellie, and Claire for your leadership and for your work in keeping students safe!

post_text:
The Imaginarium got a little face lift just in time for Thursday’s Art Fair and Imaginarium and Explorium. Classes volunteered to decorate individual letters in the word Imaginarium. They used things like paint, toys, blocks, school supplies, yarn, sticks, and gears. The letters were put together today and final product looks amazing! So much creativity at DES!
Come to the Art Fair on Thursday evening to check out the beautiful artwork and the fun gadgets in the Imaginarium.

post_text: Today our 3rd grade students participated in the MN Department of Transportation Bridge Up STEM Outreach Program. Two engineers from MN DOT shared the “Bridge in a Bag” program in which students had the opportunity to get a hands on view of the everyday work of engineers and construction workers. The Bridge UP! Curriculum gets students excited about the real work transportation planning, design, and construction of a bridge. Take a look at some of the amazing bridge designs that our 3rd graders created!

Thank you to DES parent and LDI employee Alla Johnson for her time and effort in organizing this wonderful program for DES students!

Check out our 1st grade community service project that was completed this morning. Our first grade students created 22 fleece blankets for children in foster care thanks to the donations from first grade families!
Each blanket will have a saying embroidered on it with a special saying such as “You are Loved,” and “You are Strong,” and “You are Amazing.”
A special thank you to DES parents Sara Kvasnicka and Jill VanBeusekom for your assistance with this project. DES first graders have been learning about kindness and performing Acts of Kindness each week this school year!

Are you looking to find a new home for your child’s leftover Halloween candy?
Send it to school tomorrow as we are working with Health Powered Kids by Allina Health to promote healthy living including candy in moderation, exercise and proper dental care.
For each pound of candy collected, Allina Health will donate $1 to local food shelves. The donated candy will be sent to troops overseas.

post_text: It has been a great week at DES! The highlight of the week was recognizing Unity Day. Students and staff dressed in orange to pull together against bullying and unite for kindness, acceptance and inclusion. Students took a pledge to stop bulling and created classroom banners with their fingerprint or handprint to end bullying.
